{{ref improve|date=April 2015}} A '''land Information System (LIS)''' is a [[geographic information system]] for [[cadastre|cadastral]] and [[land use|land-use]] mapping, typically used by [[local governments]].<ref>Wade, T. and Sommer, S. eds. ''[http://store.esri.com/esri/showdetl.cfm?SID=2&Product_ID=868&Category_ID=49 A to Z GIS]''</ref>
A LIS consists of an accurate, current and reliable land record [[cadastre]] and its associated attribute and spatial data that represent the legal boundaries of land tenure and provides a vital base layer capable of integration into other geographic systems or as a standalone solution that allows data stewards to retrieve, create, update, store, view, analyze and publish land information.
== Importance == # Land parcel is the basic unit for access and control of land, land use decisions. # Current, reliable land information necessary for many public programs: land planning, infrastructure development and maintenance, environmental protection and resource management, emergency services, social service programs and so forth. # LIS provides a base for land markets, development, and other economic activity. # LIS helps in updating of the maps.
